         \n                                                \n            \n        \n    \n        \n                                                                                                                                                                    \n                \n    \n    \n        \n    \n\n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n    \n        \n    \n        \n                                                                                                                                                                    \n                \n    \n    \n        \n    \n\n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n            \n    \n    \n                                                        \n                                \n                                \n                                                \n            \n        \n    \n        \n                                                                                                                                                                    \n            \n    \n    \n        \n                    \n                        \n                                    \n\n\n\n\u003cdiv id=\"article-body\" itemprop=\"articleBody\"\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"custom_block_0\"\u003e\n\u003ch3\u003eKey Takeaways\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cdiv\u003e \n\u003cul\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e Windows 11\u0026#39;s battery indicator will turn orange in energy saver mode and green when charging. \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e The updated indicator includes a feature to track battery usage over time. \u003c/li\u003e\n\u003cli\u003e Users can access the new battery indicator by downloading the Windows Dev build and using ViveTool commands. \u003c/li\u003e\n \u003c/ul\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eMany aspects of Windows have remained relatively untouched for years, even in Windows 11. For instance, while other operating systems have made better and more visually helpful battery indicators, Windows has had the same old for who knows how long now. Fortunately, a hidden feature within the Windows 11 Dev build shows us what we might expect in the future, and it looks great.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv data-include-community-rating=\"false\" id=\"e19c-4996-ae94520cf33d\" data-nosnippet=\"\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/windows-11-24h2/\"\u003e\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\" data-modal-id=\"single-image-modal\" data-modal-container-id=\"single-image-modal-container\" data-img-caption=\"\u0026#34;\u0026#34;\"\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 1024px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=422\u0026amp;h=268\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=422\u0026amp;h=268\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 768px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=310\u0026amp;h=220\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=310\u0026amp;h=220\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 481px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=720\u0026amp;h=400\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=720\u0026amp;h=400\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 0px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=432\u0026amp;h=260\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=432\u0026amp;h=260\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003cimg width=\"2400\" height=\"1600\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"Text reading Windows 11 2024 Update over a blue background\" data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\" src=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/windows-11-2024-update.jpg\"/\u003e \u003c/picture\u003e \u003c/figure\u003e \u003c/div\u003e \u003c/a\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan data-field=\"label\"\u003eRelated\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003ch5\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/windows-11-24h2/\" title=\"The Windows 11 2024 Update is now available — here\u0026#39;s what\u0026#39;s new and why it\u0026#39;s not Windows 12\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e The Windows 11 2024 Update is now available — here\u0026#39;s what\u0026#39;s new and why it\u0026#39;s not Windows 12 \u003c/a\u003e \u003c/h5\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe Windows 11 2024 Update will bring a ton of changes to the operating system, including better support for Arm devices.\u003c/p\u003e \u003c/div\u003e \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"windows-11-39-s-battery-indicator-gets-a-much-needed-makeover\"\u003e Windows 11\u0026#39;s battery indicator gets a much-needed makeover \u003c/h2\u003e\n\u003cdiv data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg\" data-modal-id=\"single-image-modal\" data-modal-container-id=\"single-image-modal-container\" data-img-caption=\"\u0026#34;\u0026#34;\"\u003e\u003cfigure\u003e\u003cpicture\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 1024px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 768px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=825\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 481px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=800\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=800\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003csource media=\"(min-width: 0px)\" data-srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=500\u0026amp;dpr=2\" srcset=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg?q=49\u0026amp;fit=crop\u0026amp;w=500\u0026amp;dpr=2\"/\u003e\u003cimg width=\"6000\" height=\"4000\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" alt=\"Angled front view of the Minisforum V3 showing the Windows 11 desktop\" data-img-url=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg\" src=\"https://static1.xdaimages.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/wm/2024/11/minisforum-v3-05.jpg\"/\u003e \u003c/picture\u003e \u003c/figure\u003e \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThis change was spotted by PhantomOfEarth, which earned a name for itself by digging through Windows Dev and Beta builds and finding hidden features. Microsoft likes to hide work-in-progress features in the testing branches before making them visible when they\u0026#39;re ready for testing. This time, PhantomOfEarth has unearthed (pun intended) a new feature within the Dev build:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe new indicator comes with some handy new features. For example, if Energy Saver has kicked in, the battery bar will turn yellow to let you know your laptop saves as much juice as possible. It also comes with a handy chart that lets you track how much battery you\u0026#39;ve used over a specific period.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIf you want to try these features, download the \u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/explaining-windows-11-insider-preview/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eWindows Dev build\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://www.xda-developers.com/how-use-vivetool-enable-features-windows-11/\" target=\"_blank\"\u003eViveTool\u003c/a\u003e. Then, use the following commands to bring the new battery charging icon out of hiding:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eUpdated battery icon: vivetool /enable /id:48822452.Section labels for the battery usage graph: vivetool /enable /id:53092139. If these commands don\u0026#39;t work, enable 48433719 and reboot.\u003c/p\u003e\n \u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eOnce done, you can then give the battery feature a try. If you don\u0026#39;t want to do all this, don\u0026#39;t fret; it should become available to everyone on the testing branch soon.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\n \u003c/div\u003e\n\n\n    \n        \n\n    \n\n        \n\n\n                \n        \n        \n\n\n        \n\n\n\n\n\n                    \n        \n    \u003c/article\u003e\n\n    \n            \n        \u003c/div\u003e\u003c/div\u003e",
